<DOC><DOCNO> AP890506-0134 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 2236EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     05-06 0173</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0178</SECOND><HEAD>Socialist Leader Speaks Out for More Democracy</HEAD><DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The leader of this country'sSocialist Party has broken with the official Communist line in apublished speech calling for more democracy and independentpolitical parties.   Socialist leader Jan Skoda, in a speech reported Friday by theSvobodne Slovo daily, made a forceful plea for a strongerparliament, independent parties, public referendums on majorissues, and academic freedom.   Czechoslovakia's ruling Communists have curbed any independentvoice for the officially tolerated Socialists and other partiessince reforms were crushed in a Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion in1968.   The Communists have recently rejected calls for reforms fromdemocratic opposition groups that they brand as anti-Communist.   ``Without substantial progress in the democratization ofpolitical, social and economic life, we shall not manage to ...gain the citizen's support for changes, whose implementation is theonly way to overcome problems the society has today,'' Skoda wasquoted as saying.   Skoda's speech stressed, however, that he wants to work withinthe system for change.</TEXT></DOC>